  "prompt": "How do you say thank you in Arabic? Does it depend on who you're speaking to?",
  "response": "The most common and versatile way to say \"thank you\" in Arabic is:\n\n*   **\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0627\u064b (Shukran)** - This is the standard and widely understood \"thank you\" in most Arabic dialects.\n\nWhile \"Shukran\" works in almost any situation, there are variations and more emphatic ways to express gratitude, and some slight regional differences:\n\n**More emphatic ways to say thank you:**\n\n*   **\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0627\u064b \u062c\u0632\u064a\u0644\u0627\u064b (Shukran Jazilan)** - \"Thank you very much.\" (Formal)\n*   **\u0623\u0644\u0641 \u0634\u0643\u0631 (Alf Shukr)** - \"A thousand thanks.\" (Common and friendly)\n*   **\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0643 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0641\u064a\u0643 (Barak Allahu Feek)** - \"May God bless you.\" (Often used in response to a thank you or as a way to show gratitude, especially among religious individuals.)\n*   **\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u064a\u062c\u0632\u064a\u0643 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u064a\u0631 (Allah yajzik al-khair)** - \"May God reward you with good.\" (Similar to Barak Allahu Feek, showing deep appreciation)\n\n**Dialectal Variations (Examples):**\n\n*   **Egyptian Arabic:** Besides \"Shukran,\" you might hear \"Mutashakker\" (\u0645\u062a\u0634\u0643\u0631) or \"Shukran Giddan\" (\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0627\u064b \u062c\u062f\u0627\u064b - \"Thank you very much\").\n*   **Levantine Arabic (Lebanon, Syria, Palestine, Jordan):** \"Shukran kteer\" (\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0627\u064b \u0643\u062a\u064a\u0631) - \"Thank you very much.\" \"Yislamo\" (\u064a\u0633\u0644\u0645\u0648) - \"May your hands be safe\" (a gesture of gratitude).\n*   **Gulf Arabic:** You might hear \"Mashkoor\" (\u0645\u0634\u0643\u0648\u0631), which is another way to say \"thank you.\"\n\n**Does it depend on who you are speaking to?**\n\nYes, to some extent, but mostly in terms of formality and depth of gratitude.\n\n*   **Formal situations (e.g., addressing someone older, in a professional setting, or someone of authority):** Use \"Shukran Jazilan\" or \"Barak Allahu Feek\" for more respect.\n*   **Informal situations (friends, family, casual acquaintances):** \"Shukran,\" \"Alf Shukr,\" or dialect-specific phrases like \"Shukran Kteer\" are fine.\n\n**In summary:**\n\n*   **\"Shukran\" is your safe bet and will be understood everywhere.**\n*   Consider using \"Shukran Jazilan\" for formal situations.\n*   Dialectal variations add a nice touch if you are familiar with the specific region.\n*   Expressions like \"Barak Allahu Feek\" and \"Allah yajzik al-khair\" show deep appreciation, particularly within religious contexts.\n\nWhen in doubt, stick with \"Shukran.\" It's polite and effective. Pay attention to how others express gratitude in the particular situation you're in to learn more nuanced uses.\n",
